<paragraph blockId="25.[151,1437,1162,1404]" pageId="25" pageNumber="226">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Downey" authorityYear="1980" box="[199,379,1197,1223]" class="Asteroidea" family="Goniasteridae" genus="Floriaster" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="25" pageNumber="226" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="maya">
<emphasis box="[199,379,1197,1223]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="226">Floriaster maya</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has only previously been known from the type locality at the southern end of the 
<collectingRegion box="[1272,1362,1198,1224]" country="Mexico" name="Yucatan" pageId="25" pageNumber="226">Yucatan</collectingRegion>
Channel. These observations are the first 
<emphasis box="[548,616,1234,1259]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="226">in situ</emphasis>
observations of this species and represent new occurrence records outside of the type locality. This species was recognized by the triangular arms (
<figureCitation box="[969,1063,1269,1295]" captionStart="FIGURE 11" captionStartId="26.[151,250,1881,1906]" captionTargetBox="[162,1428,189,1849]" captionTargetId="figure@26.[151,1436,181,1855]" captionTargetPageId="26" captionText="FIGURE 11. Floriaster maya. A. In situ feeding observation Berg Bits. B. In situ feeding observation Mona South Ridge, 1156 m. C. Abactinal surface. Scale bar=1.0 cm. D. Actinal surface. Scale bar=1.0 cm. E. Abactinal-lateral surface. Scale bar=0.5 cm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3764040" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3764040/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="226">Fig 11C</figureCitation>
), prominent pointed tubercles on the marginal plate series (
<figureCitation box="[437,536,1305,1331]" captionStart="FIGURE 11" captionStartId="26.[151,250,1881,1906]" captionTargetBox="[162,1428,189,1849]" captionTargetId="figure@26.[151,1436,181,1855]" captionTargetPageId="26" captionText="FIGURE 11. Floriaster maya. A. In situ feeding observation Berg Bits. B. In situ feeding observation Mona South Ridge, 1156 m. C. Abactinal surface. Scale bar=1.0 cm. D. Actinal surface. Scale bar=1.0 cm. E. Abactinal-lateral surface. Scale bar=0.5 cm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3764040" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3764040/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="226">Fig. 11E</figureCitation>
), the granular covering on the abactinal disk surface and the rugose granules and spines present on the actinal plate surface (
<figureCitation box="[643,744,1341,1367]" captionStart="FIGURE 11" captionStartId="26.[151,250,1881,1906]" captionTargetBox="[162,1428,189,1849]" captionTargetId="figure@26.[151,1436,181,1855]" captionTargetPageId="26" captionText="FIGURE 11. Floriaster maya. A. In situ feeding observation Berg Bits. B. In situ feeding observation Mona South Ridge, 1156 m. C. Abactinal surface. Scale bar=1.0 cm. D. Actinal surface. Scale bar=1.0 cm. E. Abactinal-lateral surface. Scale bar=0.5 cm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3764040" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3764040/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="226">Fig. 11E</figureCitation>
). Adambulacral pedicellariae abundance is higher in the collected specimen (USNM 1607582) but in all other respects, the specimen is nearly identical to the 
<typeStatus box="[1255,1357,1377,1403]" pageId="25" pageNumber="226">holotype</typeStatus>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="25" pageNumber="226" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="25.[151,1436,1449,1620]" box="[151,399,1449,1475]" pageId="25" pageNumber="226">
<emphasis box="[151,399,1449,1475]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="226">Feeding Observations</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="25.[151,1436,1449,1620]" pageId="25" pageNumber="226">
Of the four observations of this species, two observations showed this species perched vertically on what appear to be dead 
<taxonomicName box="[332,432,1521,1547]" class="Anthozoa" family="Caryophylliidae" genus="Lophelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Scleractinia" pageId="25" pageNumber="226" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[332,432,1521,1547]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="226">Lophelia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
corals (
<figureCitation box="[522,624,1521,1547]" captionStart="FIGURE 11" captionStartId="26.[151,250,1881,1906]" captionTargetBox="[162,1428,189,1849]" captionTargetId="figure@26.[151,1436,181,1855]" captionTargetPageId="26" captionText="FIGURE 11. Floriaster maya. A. In situ feeding observation Berg Bits. B. In situ feeding observation Mona South Ridge, 1156 m. C. Abactinal surface. Scale bar=1.0 cm. D. Actinal surface. Scale bar=1.0 cm. E. Abactinal-lateral surface. Scale bar=0.5 cm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3764040" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3764040/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="226">Fig. 11A</figureCitation>
) with a second feeding observation showing an individual perched on a bamboo coral stalk (
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lamouroux" authorityYear="1812" box="[380,472,1557,1584]" class="Anthozoa" family="Isididae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Alcyonacea" pageId="25" pageNumber="226" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="family">Isididae</taxonomicName>
) (
<figureCitation box="[495,597,1557,1583]" captionStart="FIGURE 11" captionStartId="26.[151,250,1881,1906]" captionTargetBox="[162,1428,189,1849]" captionTargetId="figure@26.[151,1436,181,1855]" captionTargetPageId="26" captionText="FIGURE 11. Floriaster maya. A. In situ feeding observation Berg Bits. B. In situ feeding observation Mona South Ridge, 1156 m. C. Abactinal surface. Scale bar=1.0 cm. D. Actinal surface. Scale bar=1.0 cm. E. Abactinal-lateral surface. Scale bar=0.5 cm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3764040" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3764040/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="226">Fig. 11B</figureCitation>
). This likely indicates feeding by 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Downey" authorityYear="1980" box="[978,1092,1557,1583]" class="Asteroidea" family="Goniasteridae" genus="Floriaster" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="25" pageNumber="226" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[978,1092,1557,1583]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="226">Floriaster</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
on the polyps of the coral, but could also be feeding on epizoites, such as hydroids or other organic film, growing on the dead skeletons.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
